Reflection on Bertha Wilson’s Contribution to Gender Equality in the Legal Profession -- tTaking a Stand on Equality: Bertha Wilson and the Evolution of Judicial Education in Canada -- tBertha Wilson: “Silences” in a Woman’s Life Story -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tLaw and Society0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBertha Wilson's appointment as the first female justice of the Supreme Court of Canada in 1982 capped off a career of firsts. Wilson had been the first woman lawyer and partner at a prominent Toronto law firm and the first woman appointed to the Ontario Court of Appeal. Her death in 2007 provoked reflection on her contributions to the Canadian legal landscape and raised the question, what difference do women judges make? Justice Bertha Wilson examines Wilson's career through three distinct frames and a wide range of feminist perspectives. The authors evince Wilson's contributions to the legal system in "Foundations," examine her role in high-profile decisions in "Controversy," and assess her credentials as a feminist judge and her impact on education and the profession in "Reflections." This nuanced portrait of a complex, controversial woman will appeal to lawyers, judges, policy makers, academics, and anyone interested in law and women's contributions to Canadian society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLAW / Gender & the Law.2bisacsh1 aAdjin-Tettey, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaines, Beverley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelleau, Marie-Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenedet, Janine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyd, Susan B., econtributor.4ctb4https: